sted construction projects and for the inclusion of women in apprenticeship programs. Eisenberg expected not only a challenging job and the camaraderie of a labor union but also the chance to be part of a historic transformation, social and economic, that would make the construction trades accessible to women.That transformation did not happen. In this book, full of the raw drama and humor found on a construction site, Eisenberg gracefully weaves the voices of thirty women who worked as carpenters, electricians, ironworkers, painters, and plumbers to examine why their numbers remained small. Speaking as if to a friend, women recall their decisions to enter the trades, their first days on the job, and their strategies to gain training and acceptance. They assess with thought, passion, and twenty years' perspective the affirmative action efforts. Eisenberg introduces this new edition with a preface that shows how things have changed and how they have stayed the same since the book’s original publication. She ends with a discussion of the practices and policies that would be required to uproot gender barriers where they are deeply embedded in the organization and culture of the workplace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aWomen construction workerszUnited StatesvInterviews. 4aGender Studies. 4aLabor History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171978340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501719783423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501719783/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles